FRESCO uses two primary data sources to test factual recency in re-ranker evaluation: Wikidata and historical Wikipedia revisions. Wikidata provides structured facts with explicit temporal qualifiers, capturing how facts change over time, while Wikipedia revision histories offer textual evidence corresponding to those facts at different points in time. This combination allows FRESCO to construct candidate sets that vary in semantic relevance and factual recency, isolating the challenge of selecting evidence that is both relevant and temporally valid.

